{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Hnuz54mszUGX9QFCWApE26","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01935wohxCcPK2zgo7BnyNRX","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"RabbitMQ Compliance Audit Report\n=================================\nNamespace:  karma-rabbitmq-maximal-lifecycle-roll-e44cf02f-cluster-a\nAudit date: 2026-06-23\nScope:      Read-only inspection — no changes made\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nTopology:     3-node cluster (rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2), all disk nodes\nAll running:  YES — all 3 nodes in Running state, 0 restarts on rabbitmq-{0,1,2}\nAlarms:       NONE\nNetwork partitions: NONE\nMaintenance mode:   NONE (all nodes active)\nRabbitMQ version:   3.12.14 on Erlang 25.3.2.15 (all nodes uniform)\n\n⚠  FINDING [MEDIUM] — Version out of support\n   RabbitMQ 3.12.x is flagged \"out of support\" in the node status output.\n   Recommend upgrade to a supported release series (4.0+).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n2. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nVhosts present:\n  /           (default — admin-only access)\n  /app        (application workload vhost)\n  /ops        (operations vhost)\n\nVirtual-host count: 3\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n3. USERS AND PERMISSIONS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nUsers:\n  admin     tags=[administrator]\n  app-user  tags=[management]\n  ops-user  tags=[management]\n\nPermissions per vhost:\n  / (default):\n    admin:    configure=.* write=.* read=.*\n    (no other users)\n\n  /app:\n    admin:    configure=.* write=.* read=.*\n    app-user: configure=.* write=.* read=.*\n\n  /ops:\n    admin:    configure=.* write=.* read=.*\n    ops-user: configure=.* write=.* read=.*\n\nUser limits:  None configured for any user.\nVhost limits: None configured for any vhost.\n\n⚠  FINDING [LOW] — Broad permission regexes\n   app-user and ops-user both have configure=.* / write=.* / read=.*\n   on their respective vhosts. The configure permission (.*) allows these\n   users to declare/delete queues, exchanges, and bindings. Least-privilege\n   would restrict configure to \"\" (empty — no configure access for regular\n   service accounts) unless queue declaration by the application is required.\n\n⚠  FINDING [INFO] — guest user absent\n   The guest user is not present in the user list. The config sets\n   loopback_users.guest = false (and the Erlang env shows loopback_users=[]),\n   meaning if the guest account were re-created it would be accessible from\n   any network interface. Confirm guest remains absent and this setting is\n   intentional.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n4. POLICIES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n/app:\n  Name:       ha-all\n  Pattern:    .*  (applies to all queues)\n  Apply-to:   queues\n  Priority:   0\n  Definition: {\"ha-mode\":\"all\",\"ha-sync-mode\":\"automatic\"}\n\n/ (default):  No policies\n/ops:         No policies\n\n⚠  FINDING [MEDIUM] — Classic HA mirroring (deprecated)\n   The ha-all policy uses classic mirrored queue HA (ha-mode: all).\n   Classic mirroring was deprecated in RabbitMQ 3.12 and removed in 4.0.\n   Quorum queues (x-queue-type: quorum) are the recommended replacement for\n   HA, providing stronger durability guarantees. Migrating to quorum queues\n   is required before any upgrade to RabbitMQ 4.x.\n\n⚠  FINDING [LOW] — /ops vhost has no HA policy\n   The ops-queue in /ops has no mirroring policy. If /ops carries\n   operationally important traffic, consider adding an HA or quorum-queue\n   policy for durability.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n5. QUEUES\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n/app:\n  app-queue   type=classic  durable=true  auto_delete=false\n              arguments=[x-queue-type: classic]\n              messages=775   consumers=0\n\n/ops:\n  ops-queue   type=classic  durable=true  auto_delete=false\n              arguments=[x-queue-type: classic]\n              messages=0     consumers=0\n\n⚠  FINDING [HIGH] — app-queue has 775 unprocessed messages, 0 consumers\n   There are 775 messages queued in app-queue with no active consumers.\n   Pod app-client is Running (0 restarts) but shows 0 consumers connected.\n   This indicates a consumer connectivity or application-side failure.\n   Messages will continue to accumulate. No DLX (dead-letter exchange) or\n   TTL is configured on the queue, so messages will persist indefinitely.\n   Security team should notify the application team for remediation review.\n\n⚠  FINDING [LOW] — ops-queue has 0 consumers\n   ops-queue is empty but also has no consumers. If this queue is expected\n   to be active, the ops consumer (ops-client pod) may not be connected.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n6. EXCHANGES AND BINDINGS (/app)\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nExchanges (default AMQP exchanges only — no custom exchanges declared):\n  \"\"               direct   durable=true  (default exchange)\n  amq.direct       direct   durable=true\n  amq.fanout       fanout   durable=true\n  amq.headers      headers  durable=true\n  amq.match        headers  durable=true\n  amq.topic        topic    durable=true\n  amq.rabbitmq.trace  topic durable=true  internal=true (firehose trace)\n\nBindings:\n  (default exchange) -> app-queue  routing_key=app-queue\n\nNo custom exchanges or complex routing topologies observed in /app.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n7. TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nAMQP listener:        port 5672 — plaintext (no TLS)\nManagement API:       port 15672 — plaintext HTTP (no TLS)\nPrometheus exporter:  port 15692 — plaintext HTTP (no TLS)\nClustering port:      port 25672 — plaintext (protected by Erlang cookie)\n\nssl_listeners:  [] (none configured)\nssl_options:    [] (none configured)\nTLS protocol support in Erlang runtime: TLSv1.2 and TLSv1.3 available\n  but not activated for any listener.\n\n⚠  FINDING [HIGH] — No TLS on any listener\n   All AMQP client connections and management/Prometheus traffic traverse\n   the network without encryption. Credentials, queue contents, and metrics\n   are exposed in plaintext to anyone on the pod network. Recommend enabling\n   TLS on at minimum the AMQP (5672) and Management (15672) listeners.\n\n⚠  FINDING [MEDIUM] — Management API and Prometheus exporter unauthenticated on plaintext\n   The Prometheus endpoint (15692) is accessible without TLS. Scrape traffic\n   (including per-queue and per-connection counters) is unencrypted. If the\n   scrape path is not network-restricted, consider enabling basic auth on\n   the Prometheus endpoint or restricting via NetworkPolicy.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n8. CONFIGURATION FILE REVIEW\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n/etc/rabbitmq/rabbitmq.conf (active settings):\n  cluster_formation.peer_discovery_backend = rabbit_peer_discovery_k8s\n  cluster_formation.k8s.host              = kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local\n  cluster_formation.k8s.service_name      = rabbitmq-headless\n  cluster_formation.k8s.address_type      = hostname\n  cluster_partition_handling              = pause_minority\n  queue_master_locator                    = min-masters\n  loopback_users.guest                    = false\n  listeners.tcp.default                   = 5672\n  management.tcp.port                     = 15672\n\n/etc/rabbitmq/conf.d/10-defaults.conf:\n  loopback_users.guest = false\n  log.console = true\n\nNotable:\n  - cluster_partition_handling = pause_minority: correct setting for split-brain\n    protection in a 3-node cluster.\n  - queue_master_locator = min-masters: deprecated in 3.12; has no effect for\n    quorum queues. Will be ignored after classic mirroring removal in 4.x.\n  - password_hashing_module: rabbit_password_hashing_sha256 (current default,\n    acceptable — SHA-512 is available and stronger).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n9. ENABLED PLUGINS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nrabbitmq_prometheus         (metrics scraping)\nrabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s (Kubernetes cluster formation)\nrabbitmq_management         (HTTP management API + UI)\nrabbitmq_management_agent\nrabbitmq_web_dispatch\namqp_client, cowboy, cowlib, accept, prometheus\n\nNo unexpected plugins detected. rabbitmq_management exposes the management UI\nand API; ensure access is network-restricted if not required externally.\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n10. KUBERNETES SECRETS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSecrets present in namespace (names only — values not read):\n  rabbitmq-admin        Opaque  (2 keys — admin credentials)\n  rabbitmq-app          Opaque  (2 keys — app-user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-ops          Opaque  (2 keys — ops-user credentials)\n  rabbitmq-erlang-cookie Opaque (1 key — inter-node auth cookie)\n\nCredentials are stored as Kubernetes Secrets. Audit team should verify:\n  - RBAC restricts access to these secrets to only the pods that require them.\n  - Secrets are not exposed as environment variables to unrelated workloads.\n  - The erlang cookie is rotated periodically (or at least on personnel change).\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\n11. FEATURE FLAGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nAll feature flags are enabled (15 flags). Relevant to compliance:\n  quorum_queue:       enabled (quorum queues available but not in use)\n  stream_queue:       enabled (stream queues available but not in use)\n  user_limits:        enabled\n  virtual_host_metadata: enabled\n  classic_mirrored_queue_version: enabled (classic HA mirroring active)\n\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSUMMARY OF FINDINGS\n━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━\nSeverity  Count  Items\nHIGH        2    No TLS on any listener; app-queue message backlog (775 msgs, 0 consumers)\nMEDIUM      3    RabbitMQ version out of support (3.12.14); classic HA mirroring deprecated;\n                 Management/Prometheus endpoints unauthenticated plaintext\nLOW         3    Broad configure permissions for app-user/ops-user; /ops vhost has no HA\n                 policy; ops-queue has 0 consumers\nINFO        1    guest user absent but loopback_users restriction not set\n\nNo changes were made to the cluster during this audit.\nAll data collected via read-only rabbitmqctl commands and kubectl exec.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":520,"cache_read_input_tokens":39075,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":520},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"071fc375-09e1-4c8f-b4d7-b31ebe25f198","uuid":"a60b24f6-e565-40b4-a3b0-6354e62d1405","request_id":"req_011CcLucCuRjYZE8rsrFVF9c"}
